# Workflow Rules

## Sending Handoffs
- For every outgoing handoff, write the handoff body to `./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`.
- To send it, write `.swarmforge/notify/request` with `command: send`, `target: <target-role>`, and `file: ./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`, then run `notify-agent.sh` with no arguments.
- Keep the handoff body short. Start it with: `Re-read your role and constitution.`
- Do not include branch names, commit hashes, verification notes, or implementation instructions in the body.

## Receiving Handoffs
- Save the complete incoming message to `./tmp/incoming-handoff.txt` or another local file.
- To receive it, write `.swarmforge/notify/request` with `command: receive` and `file: <saved-message-file>`, then run `notify-agent.sh` with no arguments.
- If the helper reports `DO NOT PROCESS`, stop.
- Process only accepted queue files created by the receive helper under `.swarmforge/handoffs/queue/accepted/`.
- After finishing the accepted queue file, write `.swarmforge/notify/request` with `command: complete` and `file: <accepted-queue-file>`, then run `notify-agent.sh` with no arguments.
- Do not delete accepted queue files directly.

## Cycle
- `one` sends to `two`.
- `two` sends to `three`.
- `three` sends to `four`.
- `four` sends to `five`.
- `five` sends to `six`.
- `six` sends to `one`.
- `one` is the only agent that starts by sending without first receiving a handoff.
- `two`, `three`, `four`, `five`, and `six` must wait to receive an accepted handoff before sending their handoff to the next agent.
- After `one` receives the handoff from `six`, `one` inspects all agent logbooks and reports whether every expected handoff was sent and received.
- After reporting status, `one` stops without sending another handoff.

## Final Status Check
- The final status check belongs only to `one`.
- Inspect the logbooks for `one`, `two`, `three`, `four`, `five`, and `six`.
- Confirm these sent handoffs: `one` to `two`, `two` to `three`, `three` to `four`, `four` to `five`, `five` to `six`, and `six` to `one`.
- Confirm these received handoffs: `two` from `one`, `three` from `two`, `four` from `three`, `five` from `four`, `six` from `five`, and `one` from `six`.
- Report `PASS` only if every expected sent and received handoff is present. Otherwise report `FAIL` and list the missing or inconsistent entries.
